</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="13" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="13">
The new section of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sect. Simmonsia (R. M. Schust.) Vana, Hentschel, Joch. Muell. &amp; Heinrichs" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="sect. Simmonsia (R. M. Schust.) Vana, Hentschel, Joch. Muell. &amp; Heinrichs" baseAuthorityYear="2012" class="Hepaticae" family="Scapaniaceae" genus="Scapania" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Jungermanniales" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Scapania</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subg. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Scapania</emphasis>
is characterized by its type, the dioicous 
<taxonomicName class="Hepaticae" family="Scapaniaceae" genus="Scapania" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Jungermanniales" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Scapania americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Müll">Muell</normalizedToken>
. Frib. Distinctive features of 
<taxonomicName class="Hepaticae" family="Scapaniaceae" genus="Scapania" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Jungermanniales" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Scapania americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sect. Simmonsia (R. M. Schust.) Vana, Hentschel, Joch. Muell. &amp; Heinrichs" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="sect. Simmonsia (R. M. Schust.) Vana, Hentschel, Joch. Muell. &amp; Heinrichs" baseAuthorityYear="2012" class="Hepaticae" family="Scapaniaceae" genus="Scapania" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Jungermanniales" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Scapania</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sect. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Americanae</emphasis>
are thick-walled, pigmented stem epidermis cells with thinner-walled cells on the ventral side of the stem, closely and sharply ciliate-dentate leaf-margins, with largest teeth up to five cells long and terminal cells considerably longer than wide, leaf-lobes that are usually decurrent beyond the level of the keel, a verruculose or striate-verruculose cuticle, and two-celled gemmae at the margins of unmodified leaves. The dorsal leaf-lobes often develop an undulate or folded base and may even show minute lobules or auricles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="13" type="type">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="13">
<taxonomicName class="Hepaticae" family="Scapaniaceae" genus="Scapania" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Jungermanniales" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Scapania americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Müll">Muell</normalizedToken>
. Frib., Bull. Herb. Boissier, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="sér">ser</normalizedToken>
. 2, 3: 44. 1902.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="14" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" type="note">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="14" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">
<taxonomicName class="Hepaticae" family="Scapaniaceae" genus="Scapania" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Jungermanniales" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Scapania americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is placed sister to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sect. Simmonsia (R. M. Schust.) Vana, Hentschel, Joch. Muell. &amp; Heinrichs" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="sect. Simmonsia (R. M. Schust.) Vana, Hentschel, Joch. Muell. &amp; Heinrichs" baseAuthorityYear="2012" class="Hepaticae" family="Scapaniaceae" genus="Scapania" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Jungermanniales" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Scapania</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sect. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Compactae</emphasis>
(
<normalizedToken originalValue="Müll">Muell</normalizedToken>
. Frib.) H. Buch with weak bootstrap support (
<bibRefCitation author="Heinrichs, J" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution" pageId="1" pageNumber="14" pagination="973 - 985" publicationUrl="10.1016/j.ympev.2011.11.029" refId="B2" refString="Heinrichs, J, Bombosch, A, Feldberg, K, Kreier, HP, Hentschel, J, Eckstein, J, Long, D, Zhu, RL, Schaefer-Verwimp, A, Schmidt, AR, Shaw, B, Shaw, AJ, Vana, J, 2012. A phylogeny of the northern temperate leafy liverwort genus Scapania (Scapaniaceae, Jungermanniales). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 62: 973 - 985, 10.1016/j.ympev.2011.11.029" title="A phylogeny of the northern temperate leafy liverwort genus Scapania (Scapaniaceae, Jungermanniales)." url="10.1016/j.ympev.2011.11.029" volume="62" year="2012">Heinrichs et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
). It differs from members of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sect. Simmonsia (R. M. Schust.) Vana, Hentschel, Joch. Muell. &amp; Heinrichs" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="sect. Simmonsia (R. M. Schust.) Vana, Hentschel, Joch. Muell. &amp; Heinrichs" baseAuthorityYear="2012" class="Hepaticae" family="Scapaniaceae" genus="Scapania" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Jungermanniales" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Scapania</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sect. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Compactae</emphasis>
by its dioicous condition; hence we place it in a new section rather 
<pageBreakToken pageId="1" pageNumber="14" start="start">than</pageBreakToken>
in sect. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Compactae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Fabales" pageId="1" pageNumber="14" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="14">Compactae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In our current circumscription, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sect. Simmonsia (R. M. Schust.) Vana, Hentschel, Joch. Muell. &amp; Heinrichs" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="sect. Simmonsia (R. M. Schust.) Vana, Hentschel, Joch. Muell. &amp; Heinrichs" baseAuthorityYear="2012" class="Hepaticae" family="Scapaniaceae" genus="Scapania" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Jungermanniales" pageId="1" pageNumber="14" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="14">Scapania</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sect. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="14">Americanae</emphasis>
is monospecific, however, extension of the taxon sampling in forthcoming molecular studies may disclose further representatives.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
